<HEADLINE>
<P>
THANKFUL EMIGRANT LEAVES $5.6 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An Austrian emigrant has left $5.6 million to the U.S. government as a thank 
you to the country that took them in. 
</P>
<P>
 Stanley S. Newberg, who died in 1986 at age 81 without any surviving blood 
relatives, left most of his $8.4-million estate to the government.The Justice 
Department received its $5.6 million earlier this week, U.S. Atty. Donald K. 
Stern said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 The will tied no restrictions to the gift, which was forwarded to the Bureau 
of Public Debt in Washington to be used to cover general government expenses. 
</P>
<P>
 It will cover less than two minutes of government spending, based on the 1994 
federal budget, which is $1.5 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
 Newberg married once, to a woman who had three children from a previous 
marriage, and the stepchildren, Julian and Felix Porter and Letty Pearl, 
contested the will. 
</P>
<P>
 They produced a document they said Newberg had signed that gave them half his 
assets upon his death, officials said. However, a handwriting expert determined 
the document had been forged and they settled out of court for an undisclosed 
amount. 
</P>
</TEXT>
