<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY: NEWBURY PARK; SWEET-TOOTHED THIEF BREAKS INTO VEHICLES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG RIPPEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 While residents at the Las Casitas condominium slept, an auto burglar with a 
sweet tooth and a knack for removing the window of a car without a sound 
managed to break into four vehicles, sheriff's deputies said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Sometime late Thursday or early Friday, a thief removed the back windows of 
the vehicles parked at the Newbury Park development and then removed the 
stereos or compact-disc units in the dashboards, Sheriff's Sgt. Kitty Hoberg 
said 
</P>
<P>
 In one of the cars, only candy bars were taken.The vehicles, including two 
pickup trucks, were parked in carports bordering an alley that runs between 
Paseo Esmeralda and Paseo La Perla, Hoberg said. 
</P>
<P>
 The car owners later found their back windows, intact and unbroken, beside 
their vehicles, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 "So we go from looking for kids who like candy bars to specialists who know 
how to remove windows," the sergeant said. 
</P>
<P>
 The burglaries come a week after sheriff's deputies arrested three suspects in 
connection with 13 auto burglaries in the Moorpark area. On Sept. 30, deputies 
arrested a 19-year-old man and two juveniles on suspicion of vehicle burglary. 
</P>
<P>
 Hoberg said detectives feel the three were involved with 13 auto burglaries, 
in which cellular phones were removed from unlocked cars and then offered for 
sale the next day at school. "It's one of the biggest problems we have in 
(Thousand Oaks)," she said. "The crimes are happening more frequently." 
</P>
<P>
 Of the latest burglaries, Hoberg added: "Obviously, these people are very 
proficient. . . . They may be involved in the window removal or stereo 
business." GREG RIPPEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
