<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHAMINADE GETS KNOCKED FLAT, 72-14 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VINCE KOWALICK, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Well, at least there was no running clock. 
</P>
<P>
 That's about all Chaminade High could stop from running in a 72-14 nonleague 
loss to Bloomington on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
 But then, who has been able to stop Don Markham's punch-in-the-jaw, 
double-wing attack that has run over five opponents by a combined score of 
352-45? 
</P>
<P>
 "That is the worst loss I have ever experienced -- period," Chaminade Coach 
Rich Lawson said. 
</P>
<P>
 How bad was it? Bloomington, spreading the carries among seven backs, rushed 
for 302 yards and eight touchdowns, running a play-action attack to 
near-perfection. The Bruins were marching for another score when reserve 
quarterback Chuck Webb fumbled the ball away with six minutes left. 
</P>
<P>
 Not counting the drive that was halted by halftime, it was the only possession 
in which Bloomington did not reach the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
 Chaminade (3-2), which shut out its first two opponents and yielded 
minus-eight yards rushing in its first three games, did not throw Bloomington 
for a loss until late in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 For a measure of balance, quarterback Jason Buell completed all three of his 
passes for 162 yards. Completions of 56 and 67 yards went for touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
 Bloomington outgained the Eagles, 464 yards to 100, and sacked quarterback 
Jason Zdenek six times. 
</P>
<P>
 "They're awesome," said Jason Giovannettone, who scored both Chaminade 
touchdowns but took them as a defensive back. "They had great play action. We 
couldn't see who had the ball until they were past the line." 
</P>
<P>
 The result should come as no surprise. Since the arrival this season of 
Markham, who has run his old-fashioned, run-oriented offense during coaching 
stints all over Southern California and in Oregon, Bloomington (1-9 last 
season) has been recording such lopsided victories that opposing coaches have 
charged Markham with piling on the points. 
</P>
<P>
 Two of Bloomington's games were played with a running clock in the second half 
to provide a quicker finish. But Lawson would have no mercy rules. 
</P>
<P>
 "Why run the clock?" Lawson said. "There are things we need to work on. I'm 
not going to be a crybaby about it. They came out and played football and took 
it right to us. 
</P>
<P>
 "The only thing that bothered me is, they were rushing our punter right 'til 
the end." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Markham: "This is a practice game. We need to work on things." 
</P>
<P>
 Bloomington's Cheyane Caldwell gained 159 yards in 13 carries and scored two 
touchdowns. Greg Oliver had 77 yards and three touchdowns in eight carries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
